EUROEVOL_R app, mapping EUROEVOL database radiocarbon datings

Thomas Huet

Presentation

The EUROEVOL_R app is a RShiny interactive web application which allows the selection of radiocarbon dating by location, chronology and material life duration by subsetting EUROEVOL database radiocarbon dataset according to:

  • a geographical region of interest (ROI)
  • a time span between a tpq and a taq in cal BC
  • some periods (Late Mesolithic, Early Neolithic, etc.)
  • some type of material life duration (short like, long life or others)
  • a maximum accepted standard deviation threshold (SD)

We will see how to use the app, and how the app works with EUROEVOL database

the EUROEVOL_R app

The EUROEVOL database

The EUROEVOL database is an impressive open source database covering the Central, Western and Northern Europe from Paleolithic times to the end of Bronze Age (ca. 17,000 - 500 BC). For these periods, the EUROEVOL database gather one of the most complete datasets for archaeobotany, archaeozoology and radiocarbon datings. This latter register scores more than 14,000 radiocarbon datations (Manning et al. 2016).

Below, we present how these data can be read with R and adapted to serve the EUROEVOL_R app

Data structure

The EUROEVOL database are recorded into different online .csv files as the result of a MySQL database export (Manning et al. 2016).

library(dplyr)

Data reading and clean-up

The content of these .csv files that can be easily read by R, the different tables can be joined on id fields (SiteID, PhaseCode, etc.) and some changes must be done on the types of data

S.Com <- read.csv(url(SitCom.url), stringsAsFactors = F)
ChrPh <- read.csv(url(ChrPh.url), stringsAsFactors = F) 
C14 <- read.csv(url(C14.url), stringsAsFactors = F)
ChrPh <- subset(ChrPh,select=c("Culture","PhaseCode")) # only interesting colnames
# joins
df.C14 <- merge(S.Com,C14,by="SiteID",all.x=T) # C14
df.C14 <- merge(df.C14,ChrPh,by="PhaseCode",all.x=T) # culture names
# type
df.C14$Latitude <- as.numeric(as.character(df.C14$Latitude))
df.C14$Longitude <- as.numeric(as.character(df.C14$Longitude))
Encoding(df.C14$SiteName) <- "UTF-8"
df.C14[df.C14 == "NULL"] <- NA # to NA
df.C14 <- df.C14[!is.na(df.C14$C14ID),]# rm C14 is NA
df.C14$Period[is.na(df.C14$Period)] <- "NoPeriod"
# show
kable(head(df.C14, 11),"html") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "center", font_size=11)

Radiocarbon calibration

R offers different package for radiocarbon calibrations, like the Bchron package. Because the calibration process of such a large dataset could be long, so we will only select a sample of 10 datings in this example.

library(Bchron)
df.C14.sample <- df.C14[sample(1:nrow(df.C14),10),] # sample
ages <- BchronCalibrate(ages=df.C14.sample$C14Age, 
                        ageSds=df.C14.sample$C14SD, 
                        calCurves=rep(x = 'intcal13',nrow(df.C14.sample)))

The result of the BchronCalibrate function is a list where each calibrated dating (eg, ages[[1]]) is described by:

  • ages: an age (in uncal BP)
  • ageSds: a standard deviation (SD)
  • calCurves: the calibration curve used (intcal13, etc.)
  • ageGrid: a vector with all the years present in the calibration range (in cal BP)
  • densities: the densities of each year present in the calibration range

To illustrate this calibration, we only plot the first dating

str(ages[[1]])
## List of 5
##  $ ages     : int 4590
##  $ ageSds   : int 100
##  $ calCurves: chr "intcal13"

##  $ densities: num [1:816] 1.09e-05 1.23e-05 1.39e-05 1.57e-05 1.73e-05 ...

Datings are still in BP. In archaeology, a standardised way will be to present them in cal BC. Furthermore, our purpose is to calculate terminus post quem (tpq) and terminus ante quem (taq) limits of each radiocarbon dating in order to use these termini for subsetting the dataset in the EUROEVOL_R app

tpqs <- taqs <- c()
for (i in 1:length(ages)){
  tpqs <- c(tpqs, -max(ages[[i]]$ageGrid))
  taqs <- c(taqs, -min(ages[[i]]$ageGrid))
}
# to bc
df.C14.sample$tpq <- tpqs + 1950
df.C14.sample$taq <- taqs + 1950
kable(df.C14.sample,"html", row.names = F) %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, position = "center", font_size=10)

Once calculated, the dataset can be saved and will be re-read in the RShiny app

## nor run
# write.csv(df.C14.sample, file = "euroevol.csv", sep = ";")

Final remarks

Here, our purpose was calculate tpq and taq for the interactive subsetting of the dataset with the slider tpq/taq of the EUROEVOL_R app map panel. But in the app, for each date selected, a such calibration will be performed on-the-fly and the whole density curve will be displayed on the calib panel
